# PresenterKit — Development Conventions

Project structure: `apps/backend` (NestJS + TypeORM + PostgreSQL) and `apps/frontend` (Next.js 16 + React 19 + styled-components).

---

## General TypeScript

- Strict TypeScript everywhere — no `any`; use `unknown` with narrowing when type is external.
- Always declare types for function parameters and return values.
- Use `interface` for object shapes; use `type` for unions, intersections, and mapped types.
- Use `readonly` for immutable properties; `as const` for literal constants.
- Name boolean variables with auxiliary verbs: `isLoading`, `hasError`, `canDelete`.
- Use PascalCase for classes and interfaces; camelCase for variables and functions; kebab-case for file and directory names.
- Use complete words over abbreviations. Accepted exceptions: `i`/`j` for loops, `err` for errors, `ctx` for contexts, `req`/`res`/`next` for middleware.
- Start function names with a verb. Booleans → `isX`/`hasX`/`canX`; void functions → `executeX`/`saveX`.
- Keep functions short and single-purpose (aim for < 20 statements).
- Avoid deep nesting — use early returns and guard clauses instead.
- Use the RORO (Receive Object, Return Object) pattern for functions with multiple parameters.
- Use `async/await` over raw Promises.
- No magic numbers — define named constants.

---

## Backend (`apps/backend`) — NestJS

### Module Architecture

- One module per main domain (`auth`, `files`, `events`, `public-upload`).
- Each module owns: a controller, DTOs (`dto/`), entities (`entities/`), interfaces (`interfaces/`), service(s), and tests (`tests/`).
- `config/` holds environment configuration via `@itgorillaz/configify`.
- `logging/` holds Pino setup — do not add ad-hoc console logs.
- Cross-cutting concerns (guards, filters, interceptors) live in a `core` module — do not scatter them.
- Shared utilities go in a `shared` module.

### Controllers and Services

- Controllers only handle HTTP concerns (routing, parsing, response mapping) — no business logic.
- Services own business logic and persistence. One service per entity.
- Use `class-validator` + `class-transformer` for all DTO validation — never validate manually in service methods.
- Return plain typed objects from services; avoid returning entity instances directly to controllers.

### Authentication

- JWT via `@nestjs/jwt` + Passport strategies. Do not bypass guards.
- Passwords hashed with Argon2 — never store or log plaintext passwords.
- Cookies managed via `cookie-parser`.

### Database (TypeORM + PostgreSQL)

- Use `TIMESTAMPTZ` for all timestamp columns, never `TIMESTAMP` without timezone.
- Use `UUID` for public-facing IDs; prefer auto-generated PKs for internal keys.
- All FK columns must have explicit `ON DELETE` behavior defined.
- Never use `SELECT *` — always select explicit columns.
- Add LIMIT on all potentially large queries.

### Logging

- Use Pino via `nestjs-pino` — it is already configured in `logging/`.
- Log at `info` for normal operations, `warn` for unexpected-but-recoverable states, `error` for failures.
- Never log sensitive data (passwords, tokens, PII).

### Error Handling

- Use NestJS exception filters for consistent HTTP error responses.
- Throw NestJS built-in HTTP exceptions (`NotFoundException`, `BadRequestException`, etc.) from services when appropriate.
- Use a global exception filter for unhandled errors — do not silence them.

### Testing (Jest)

- Test files live in `tests/` within each module (e.g., `auth/tests/`).
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert in unit tests.
- Name variables: `inputX`, `mockX`, `actualX`, `expectedX`.
- Use Jest mocks for external dependencies (Azure Blob, Resend email, etc.).
- Write at least one unit test per public service method.

