## Frontend (`apps/frontend`) — Next.js + React

### Project Structure

```
src/
  app/                        # Next.js App Router routes
  ui/
    components/               # Reusable UI library components
    theme/                    # styled-components theme and global styles
  lib/
    api/                      # ky-based API clients (one file per resource)
    stores/                   # Zustand stores (one file per domain)
    hooks/                    # Shared hooks (used across multiple features)
    utils/                    # Pure utility functions
    sse/                      # Server-Sent Events helpers
```

#### Route folder (`src/app/<route>/`)

```
<route>/
  page.tsx          # Route entry point
  layout.tsx        # (optional) Route layout
  styled.ts         # Page-level styled components
  schemas.ts        # (optional) Zod schemas for all forms on this route
  schemas.test.ts   # (optional) Schema unit tests
  page.test.tsx     # (optional) Page-level tests
  partials/         # Sub-components used only by this route
```

#### Partial / feature component (`partials/<Name>/`)

```
<Name>/
  <Name>.tsx        # Component implementation
  styled.ts         # Local styled components
  index.ts          # Barrel export
  <Name>.test.tsx   # (optional) Component tests
  hooks/            # (optional) Hooks local to this component
    use<Name>.ts
  types.ts          # (optional) Component-specific types
  partials/         # (optional) Nested sub-components, same structure recursively
```

#### UI library component (`src/ui/components/<Name>/`)

```
<Name>/
  <Name>.tsx        # Component implementation
  <Name>.styled.ts  # Styled components (prefixed unlike route partials)
  <Name>.types.ts   # TypeScript types
  index.ts          # Barrel export
  <Name>.icons.ts   # (optional) Icon/asset registry
```

### Components

- Use functional components only.
- Use `function` declarations for top-level components — not `const` arrow functions.
- One component per file; named exports only.
- Component types (props, local types) live in a `types.ts` within the same co-located folder.
- Hooks local to a component live in that component's `partials/` folder. Only hooks shared across multiple features go in `src/lib/hooks/`.
- Keep component files small — extract sub-components and helpers when a file grows unwieldy.

### Styling (styled-components)

- All styling via styled-components — no inline `style` props except for truly dynamic values.
- For locally-scoped styled components (used only within their file), keep names short and generic: `Container`, `Title`, `Wrapper`. Only prefix with the component name (e.g. `CardTitle`) when the styled component is exported or shared across files.
- Before creating a new UI element, check `src/ui/components/` first. Use the existing component if one fits; create a new one there only if nothing suitable exists.
- Use `ThemeProvider` and the project theme from `src/ui/theme/` for all design tokens (colors, spacing, typography).
- Use the `css` helper for conditional/complex style blocks.
- Add proper TypeScript prop types to styled components that accept props for dynamic styling.
- Do not mix styled-components with Tailwind or other styling solutions.

### Data Fetching (TanStack Query v5)

- TanStack Query manages all server state — do not duplicate fetched data into Zustand.
- Always define `queryOptions()` outside components, never inline inside `useQuery()`.
- Use a query key factory pattern per resource (e.g., `fileKeys`, `eventKeys`).
- Mutations invalidate the relevant query keys on success.
- Use `useSuspenseQuery` with `<Suspense>` + error boundary wrappers for data-dependent UI.
- Never use `useEffect` to fetch data.
- API calls go in `src/lib/api/` — one file per resource using the `ky` client from `client.ts`.

### Client State (Zustand)

- Zustand is for shared client-only state (e.g., `display.store`, `preview.store`, `timeline.store`).
- Do not put server/fetched data in Zustand — that belongs in TanStack Query.
- Each store is domain-focused. Define explicit `State` and `Actions` interfaces.
- Subscribe to the smallest needed slice: `useStore((s) => s.value)`.
- Use `useShallow` when selecting multiple values at once.
- Use functional `set((state) => …)` when next state depends on current state.
- Never persist secrets or auth tokens to browser storage.
- Do not create a single global store for everything.

### Forms (React Hook Form + Zod)

- All forms use `react-hook-form` with `@hookform/resolvers/zod`.
- Zod schemas live in a route-level `schemas.ts` (e.g. `src/app/auth/schemas.ts`) — one file per route grouping all its form schemas. Export inferred types (`z.infer<typeof schema>`) from the same file.
- Show field-level validation errors using the `formState.errors` object.
- Async submit errors should be surfaced to the user — not silently swallowed.

### Error Handling

- Use error boundaries (`error.tsx` in App Router) for unexpected rendering errors.
- API errors thrown from `src/lib/api/` are caught by TanStack Query and surfaced via `isError`/`error`.
- Do not use `try/catch` for expected API errors in query functions — let TanStack Query handle them.

### Next.js App Router

- Most routes (`/auth`, `/dashboard`, `/upload`) are client components — they rely heavily on hooks and do not need SEO optimization. Mark them with `'use client'`.
- Only the main public-facing page uses React Server Components for SEO. Do not add RSC to pages that don't need it.
- Optimize images: use `<Image>` from `next/image` with explicit `width`/`height` or `fill`.

### Testing (Vitest + Testing Library)

- Unit and component tests use Vitest + `@testing-library/react`.
- Mock dependencies with `vi.mock()` before imports.
- Follow Arrange-Act-Assert. Group related tests in `describe` blocks with descriptive names.

